d":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tipping","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and West Midlands):","from a Middle English and Old English personal name <i>Tipping</i>, a pet form of Old English <i>Tippa</i>, for which there is evidence in placenames such as Tiptree, but which is of uncertain origin. See   Tipp  .","from the Middle English personal name <i>Tipun</i> or <i>Tipin</i>, diminutives of the personal name   Tipp   or <i>Tibb</i> (see   Tibbs  ). The name was probably later absorbed by <i>Tipping</i>, <i>Tippin</i>, and <i>Tippen</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Tipp","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Tibb</b> (see   Tibbs  ).","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Tipp</i> (Old English <i>Tippa</i>, of uncertain origin). Compare   Tipping  .","North German: from Low German <i>tippe</i>, <i>tibbe</i> ‘wooden pail, small tub’, perhaps a metonymic occupational name for a maker of those."]},{"name":"Tippin","meanings":["English: variant of   Tipping  ."]},{"name":"Tippen","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Tipping  ."]},{"name":"Tippins","meanings":["English (Herefordshire and Gloucestershire): variant of   Tipping  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is also found in Monmouthshire, Wales."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":22,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":31,